1️⃣ If-Else (Decision Making)
Simple Idea

👉 If-Else lets the program make decisions

Real-World Example

Think of this:

If it is raining → take umbrella  
Else → don’t take
C++ Example
int age = 18;

if(age >= 18)
{
    cout << "Eligible to vote";
}
else
{
    cout << "Not eligible";
}
What Actually Happens

Condition checked:

age >= 18  → TRUE

If TRUE → run if block

Else → run else block

Mental Model (Never Forget)
IF → decision gate  
Condition → key  

Like a security gate:

Valid ID → enter

Invalid → reject

Why It Works

Because of boolean logic (true/false)

Computer only understands:

1 → true  
0 → false
Flow Visualization
Condition check
      ↓
 TRUE      FALSE
  ↓          ↓
IF block   ELSE block
Important Variations
1. Only if
if(x > 0)
{
    cout << "Positive";
}
2. Multiple conditions
if(marks >= 90)
    cout << "A";
else if(marks >= 75)
    cout << "B";
else
    cout << "C";
Connection to Real Life

Every decision you make:

If hungry → eat  
If tired → sleep  

👉 Same logic in programming

Common Mistake 🔥
if(x = 5)  // ❌ wrong

👉 This assigns value, not compares

Correct:

if(x == 5)  // ✅
How to Remember

Just think:

IF = decision  
ELSE = fallback
2️⃣ Loops (Repeating Work)
Simple Idea

👉 Loop = repeat something multiple times

Real-World Example
Brush teeth daily  
Attend class every day  

👉 Repetition = loop

1. for Loop (Most Used in Placements)
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++)
{
    cout << i;
}
What Happens Step-by-Step
i = 1 → print  
i = 2 → print  
i = 3 → print  
i = 4 → print  
i = 5 → print  
stop
Mental Model
for loop = counter-controlled machine
Structure Breakdown
for(initialization; condition; update)
Part	Meaning
initialization	start point
condition	when to stop
update	how it moves
Visual Flow
Start → Check → Run → Update → Repeat
2. while Loop
int i = 1;

while(i <= 5)
{
    cout << i;
    i++;
}
Difference from for loop
for	while
when count is known	when count is unknown
Real-Life Example
While you are hungry → keep eating
🔥 Important Concept: Infinite Loop
while(true)
{
    cout << "Hello";
}

👉 Runs forever

Why Loops Matter

Without loop:

cout << 1;
cout << 2;
cout << 3;

With loop:

for(int i=1; i<=3; i++)
    cout << i;

👉 Cleaner + scalable

Connection to What You Know

Math sequences:

1, 2, 3, 4, 5

👉 Generated using loop

